American healt care data analysis¶

Goal:¶

To show all I'm capable of. I do not take this project as an analysis rather as a demonstration of all my tools.

The whole document is divided into 3 parts.

  1. Cleaning
  • Here, I am preparing data for further analysis.
  1. Analysis and visualizations
  • In this part, I am trying to describe variables through statistics and visualize them. For example, I am using correlations, boxplots, or histograms.
  1. Hypothesis testing
  • This is the last part where I am testing some hypotheses about BMI in the US. I am using tools as t-test, ANOVA, or others.

Graphical one¶

In [11]:
def create_histogram_pandas(data, name):
    max_number = data.median()
    min_number = data.min()
    to_norm = lambda x: (x - min_number)/(max_number - min_number)
    data = data.apply(to_norm)
    plt.clf
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
    plt.hist(data, bins=50)
    plt.title(name)
    plt.show()

create_histogram_pandas(insurance.bmi, "bmi")
create_histogram_pandas(insurance.age, "age")
create_histogram_pandas(insurance.charges, "charges")

Hyphothesis testing¶

In [18]:
#used DIY functions
def two_samples_validate(sample1, sample2, threshold):
    pval = stats.ttest_ind(sample1, sample2)[1]
    if threshold > 0.1:
        print("Are you sure to use threshold bigger then 0.1?")
    if pval > threshold:
        print("P-value isn't significant.")
        return pval
    elif pval < threshold:
        print("P-value is significant.")
        return pval
    else:
        print("Validation Error!")
def validate(pval, threshold):
    if threshold > 0.1:
        print("Are you sure to use threshold bigger then 0.1?")
    if pval > threshold:
        print("P-value isn't significant.")
        return False
    elif pval < threshold:
        print("P-value is significant.")
        return True
    else:
        print("Validation Error!")

BMI and region¶

Null: There is no difference in average BMI between regions.

In [20]:
#separating bmi according to regions
southwest = insurance[insurance.region == "southwest"].bmi
southeast = insurance[insurance.region == "southeast"].bmi
northeast = insurance[insurance.region == "northeast"].bmi
northwest = insurance[insurance.region == "northwest"].bmi

#ANOVA
pval_anova = stats.f_oneway(southwest, southeast, northeast, northwest)[1]
anova_significance = validate(pval_anova, 0.05)
print("Not all region has same bmi, so it is time dig deeper.")

#Tukey test
tukey_results = pairwise_tukeyhsd(insurance.bmi, insurance.region)
print(tukey_results)

P-value is significant.
Not all region has same bmi, so it is time dig deeper.

Bmi and gender¶

Null: There is no difference in precetage of obese people (BMI > 30) between man and women

In [23]:
# before I can say if the precentage is different. I need to find the precentages.
def find_obese(data, level):
    num_obese = 0
    for i in range(len(data)):
        if data.iloc[i].bmi > level:
            num_obese += 1
    prec_obese = num_obese/ len(data) * 100
    return prec_obese
In [24]:
prec_obese_men = find_obese(men, 30)
prec_obese_women = find_obese(women, 30)
print("In data we have {} % obese men and {} % obese women.".format(np.round(prec_obese_men, decimals=2), np.round(prec_obese_women, decimals= 2)))

In data we have 54.88 % obese men and 50.45 % obese women.
In [25]:
# no is time to test if we are able to get % of obese men with women and vice versa.
# prec-men + women data
p_value_women = stats.binom_test(prec_obese_women/100, len(women), prec_obese_men/100, alternative= "greater")
significance_women= validate(p_value_women, 0.05)

# prec-women + men data
p_value_men = stats.binom_test(prec_obese_men/100, len(men), prec_obese_women/100)
significance_men= validate(p_value_men, 0.05)

print("P-value women: {}".format(p_value_women))
print("P_value men: {}".format(p_value_men))

P-value isn't significant.
P-value is significant.
P-value women: 1.0
P_value men: 6.772008395660982e-207

It seems like the precentage of obese men can't be easier reached. To confirm this idea I will perform two sample test to say if avarage BMI between men is different to avearage between women.
